{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531106"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:11:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:11:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14579"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14579"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.32,0.52,0.06,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7272"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57092"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7272"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14579"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42551"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"81"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"1675"},{"type":"tags","id":"2718"},{"type":"tags","id":"4857"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17749"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36989"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43539"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57092"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old woman is admitted to the general medical ward following a syncopal episode. She lost consciousness briefly while standing up from a sitting position in her garden. The episode was witnessed by her husband, who was sitting nearby. There was no post-ictal confusion, no seizure activity, and no preceding symptoms. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has a medical history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, peripheral vascular disease, and bilateral cataract surgery. She is an ex-smoker with a 40 pack-year history. Her medications include metformin, perindopril, and aspirin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg supine, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECardiovascular, respiratory, abdominal, and detailed neurological examinations are unremarkable. On standing, her blood pressure drops to 120/75 mmHg without a compensatory increase in heart rate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer ECG was unremarkable with no ventricular pause or heart block. She has had blood tests performed but the results are still pending at the time of your review.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of her syncope?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vertebrobasilar insufficiency","Vasovagal syncope","Autonomic neuropathy","Carotid sinus hypersensitivity","Postprandial hypotension"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of orthostatic hypotension due to autonomic dysfunction. The key finding is a significant postural drop in blood pressure (25 mmHg systolic) without an appropriate compensatory increase in heart rate, suggesting impaired autonomic reflexes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutonomic neuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given her long-standing type 2 diabetes and the pattern of autonomic dysfunction. Diabetes can affect both sympathetic and parasympathetic nerve fibres, leading to impaired cardiovascular reflexes and orthostatic hypotension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasovagal syncope\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs with a prodrome of sweating, nausea, and pallor, often triggered by emotional stress or prolonged standing. It would be unusual to occur with simple positional change and would typically show both a drop in blood pressure and heart rate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid sinus hypersensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs with head turning or neck pressure and would not be triggered by standing from a sitting position. It is more common in elderly patients but does not fit the pattern described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPostprandial hypotension\u003C/strong\u003E occurs after meals due to blood pooling in the splanchnic circulation. While this can occur in diabetic autonomic neuropathy, the history does not suggest a relationship to meals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVertebrobasilar insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with additional neurological symptoms such as vertigo, diplopia, or ataxia, which are absent in this case. The clear relationship to postural change makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Orthostatic hypotension without compensatory heart rate increase suggests autonomic dysfunction.","Diabetes is a common cause of autonomic neuropathy in older adults.","A drop in systolic blood pressure \u003E20 mmHg on standing is diagnostic of orthostatic hypotension."],"references":["Marfella R. Characteristics of geriatric DM patients. JOURNAL OF GERONTOLOGY AND GERIATRICS. 2021 Dec 16;69:233-7. Available online at ; file:///C:/Users/61432/Downloads/447-Manuscript%20file-2651-2-10-20231108%20(1).pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42551"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14579"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42551"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-24T14:26:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-24T14:27:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7272"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57092"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"81","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/81"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diabetes mellitus","synonyms":["DM","Diabetes"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-20T08:10:02+09:30","updat